178
00:09:28,759 --> 00:09:31,039
around seeking help
for mental health issues.

179
00:09:31,120 --> 00:09:33,960
And especially now, given that,
over the last two years,

180
00:09:34,039 --> 00:09:35,879
we have seen a spike in them.

181
00:09:35,960 --> 00:09:39,039
During the pandemic,
about "four in 10 adults in the U.S.

182
00:09:39,120 --> 00:09:41,919
have reported symptoms
of anxiety or depressive disorder."

183
00:09:42,000 --> 00:09:45,200
That's up from one in 10
who reported them a year before.

184
00:09:45,279 --> 00:09:47,759
It may help explain why,
for that one month last year,

185
00:09:47,840 --> 00:09:51,559
everyone on the internet
suddenly started singing sea shanties.

186
00:09:51,960 --> 00:09:54,559
It was clearly
a collective cry for help.

187
00:09:55,600 --> 00:09:59,399
So, encouraging people to talk
to someone is a very good idea.

188
00:09:59,480 --> 00:10:01,480
But as people increasingly
do seek help,

189
00:10:01,559 --> 00:10:04,919
they're discovering a system
that is just not set up to provide it.

190
00:10:05,000 --> 00:10:07,679
There have long been waitlists
to see a therapist,

191
00:10:07,759 --> 00:10:10,600
but it has gotten significantly worse
since the pandemic,

192
00:10:10,679 --> 00:10:15,799
with 65% of psychologists reporting
they had no capacity for new patients.

193
00:10:15,879 --> 00:10:17,840
In fact,
"more than half the people

194
00:10:17,919 --> 00:10:20,919
who need mental health care
do not receive it,"

195
00:10:21,000 --> 00:10:24,320
with that rate being even higher
for minority populations.

196
00:10:24,399 --> 00:10:28,240
Emergency rooms are now becoming
overloaded with people,

197
00:10:28,320 --> 00:10:29,679
and especially children,

198
00:10:29,759 --> 00:10:32,720
who have nowhere else to go,
stuck in beds there,

199
00:10:32,799 --> 00:10:35,679
because there is no space
in proper facilities to treat them.

200
00:10:35,759 --> 00:10:38,919
Just take this couple,
whose 14-year-old was in crisis,

201
00:10:39,000 --> 00:10:40,600
and who followed
their pediatrician's advice

202
00:10:40,679 --> 00:10:42,440
to go to the ER with him.

203
00:10:43,000 --> 00:10:46,919
I remember we got out of the car,
and we hugged him and we said,

204
00:10:47,000 --> 00:10:51,799
"We're going to do
whatever it takes to help you."

205
00:10:52,240 --> 00:10:53,960
But once inside,
staff told them

206
00:10:54,039 --> 00:10:57,480
